history.content: I took 61B, 70, 16A and it was completely fine and I had a lot of spare time. 16B is a bit more work than 16A so it's still probably fine

children.subject: Why do you think it was harder? How much prior experience in the specific topics of those classes did you have going in?

It wasn't so much the experience as it was the sheer workload. EE 40 labs were very annoying, and 61B projects were also very high workload. I had experience in both though, so conceptually, wasn't that bad. CS 70 I wasn't great at though, and definitely was the hardest for me conceptually. 

Basically for me, CS 70 difficulty + EE 40 and 61B workload made it a very bad semester.

Ok, thanks. Do you have a good sense of whether 16B is more or less workload than 40 was? For example, at least in 16A, lab is a very predictable maximum 3hrs a week, so not that annoying, and I think 16B is similar. What was so annoying about 40 labs?
I did 61B, 70, and EE 40 and absolutely hated it. It was doable, but it was also my worst semester GPA-wise here. I'd drop 16B for a lower workload class if possible.
The xxB classes are more work than xxAs
I took the exact same classes last semester! It was a lot of work I have to say, but you probably won't die especially since you seem quite prepared (I knew Java, some 70, and half of EE16B).

history.content: I'm considering taking CS61B, EE16B, and CS70 next semester. How large of a workload is this? I've heard everywhere from doable to terrible. Since I already know Java, a lot of CS theory, and some graph theory / other 70ish math concepts, I don't anticipate having much difficulty with conceptual understanding of the material, at least in the CS classes, but how much work is EE16B compared to EE16A, CS61B compared to CS61A, etc? That's my primary concern.
history.subject: CS61B, EE16B, CS70: how doable?
